The backbone LLM [ 12 , 57 , 4 , 58 , 27 ] consists of multiple decoder layers that compute causal self-attention values. The input sequence X X to each layer consists of system, image, and text tokens given by X = [ x sys ; x img ; x txt ] ∈ ℝ L × D X=[x_{\text{sys}};x_{\text{img}};x_{\text{txt}}]\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times D} , where L L is the total input length and D D is the hidden dimension. Three weight matrices W Q , W K , W V ∈ ℝ D × D W_{Q},W_{K},W_{V}\in\mathbb{R}^{D\times D} are used to compute the query Q Q , key K K , and value V V as:

Q = X ​ W Q , K = X ​ W K , V = X ​ W V Q=XW_{Q},\quad K=XW_{K},\quad V=XW_{V}

Then, attention value A A is computed as: A ​ ( Q , K ) = Softmax ​ ( Q ​ K T + M D ) , O = A ​ V . A(Q,K)=\text{Softmax}\left(\frac{QK^{T}+M}{\sqrt{D}}\right),O=AV. where Q ∈ ℝ L × D Q\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times D} and K ∈ ℝ L × D K\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times D} . A lower triangular causal mask M ∈ ℝ L × L M\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times L} is applied to ascertain each token to attend to only the previous tokens and itself. Self-attention in transformer-based LVLMs enables these models to capture a wide range of visual contexts and nuances. However, the quadratic complexity O ​ ( N 2 ) O(N^{2}) of the attention block to compute attention values during training and inference has become a critical computational bottleneck [ 59 ] , necessitating the adoption of optimizations to reduce computational demands.
